<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,500]" pageId="4" pageNumber="291">
<bibRefCitation box="[151,523,151,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="291" refId="ref4596" refString="Monne, M. A. &amp; Giesbert, E. F. (1992) Nomenclatural notes on Western Hemisphere Cerambycidae (Coleoptera). Insecta Mundi, 6 (1 - 2), 249 - 255." type="journal article">Monné, M.A. &amp; Giesbert, 1992</bibRefCitation>
: 252 proposed the synonymy of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Monne, M. A. &amp; Martins" authorityYear="1976" box="[909,1160,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Paracobelura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="291" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curiosa">
<emphasis box="[909,1160,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="291">Paracobelura curiosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName authority="Breuning, 1943" authorityName="Breuning" authorityYear="1943" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Periestola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="291" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="strandi">
<emphasis box="[1231,1435,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="291">Periestola strandi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[151,329,188,213]" pageId="4" pageNumber="291" refId="ref3453" refString="Breuning, S. (1943) Novae species Cerambycidarum. XII. Folia Zoologica et Hydrobiologica, 12, 12 - 66." type="journal article">Breuning, 1943</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but a detailed examination of both species allowed us to propose the reinstatement and the new combination of 
<emphasis box="[328,582,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="291">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Monne, M. A. &amp; Martins" authorityYear="1976" box="[328,578,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Paracobelura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="291" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curiosa">Paracobelura curiosa</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,500]" pageId="4" pageNumber="291">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Monné &amp; Monné" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Monne &amp; Martins" baseAuthorityYear="1976" box="[199,397,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Cobelura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="291" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curiosa">
<emphasis box="[199,397,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="291">Cobelura curiosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Breuning" authorityYear="1943" box="[711,824,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Periestola" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="291" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="strandi">
<emphasis box="[711,824,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="291">C. strandi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the sides of the pronotum covered with yellowish pubescence, the elytra with three longitudinal rows of linear spots of yellowish pubescence, and the extremity of the elytra less projected than 
<taxonomicName box="[504,659,332,357]" pageId="4" pageNumber="291" rank="subSpecies" subSpecies="strandi">
in 
<emphasis box="[538,659,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="291">C. strandi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[659,663,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="291">.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[674,830,332,357]" pageId="4" pageNumber="291" rank="subSpecies" subSpecies="strandi">
In 
<emphasis box="[710,830,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="291">C. strandi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[830,834,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="291">,</emphasis>
the pronotum is uniformly covered with brownish pubescence, the elytra lacks longitudinal rows of yellowish pubescence, and the extremity of each elytron is strongly and acutely projected.
</paragraph>
